    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "yo i was doing some sprints today and my legs felt like they were on fire lol. can u explain what actually happens with the lactic acid when u push that hard? like how does it get made and how does it go away?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "When you sprint, your muscles are working hard and produce energy faster than your body can supply oxygen. As a result, they switch to anaerobic metabolism, which leads to the production of lactic acid. This lactic acid builds up in your muscles, causing that burning sensation. To get rid of it, your body eventually uses the lactic acid as a fuel source or breaks it down into lactate and hydrogen ions, which are then transported to your liver to be converted back into glucose or used as energy. The burning sensation typically subsides once the lactic acid has been cleared or converted.",
